ting connections between Marxist thought and Heidegger and features Derrida’s signature reconsideration of the dichotomy between doing and thinking. This text, available for the first time in English, shows that Derrida was doing important work on Marx long before Specters of Marx. As with the other volumes in this series, it gives readers an unparalleled glimpse into Derrida’s thinking at its best—spontaneous, unpredictable, and groundbreaking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPhilosophy, Marxist. 0aPractice (Philosophy). 0aTheory (Philosophy). 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aderrida, deconstructionism, marxism, louis althusser, thinking, acting, reason, rationality, human nature, impulse, intent, motivation, theses on feuerbach, heidegger, doing, nonfiction, philosophy, literature, classics, spontaneity, social theory, production, reproduction, technology, translated works, action, agency, independence, free will, individuals, society, class, freedom.1 aBennington, Geoffrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKamuf, Peggy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWills, David.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071194340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226572482423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226572482/original  a978-3-11-071194-3  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles